				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Hero
				</h2>
				

						
						
							
						
				<div class="content ">
					<div id="post_message_1731237">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							&quot;So,&quot;  she said, &quot;when one of the stewin' rabbits got loose, I was <br />
huntin' around the camp for it, and I finally caught it hidin' in the <br />
flour sack.  I locked it up, and went back to makin' breakfast.  For a <br />
treat, I whipped up a batch o' plain muffins.  While I was warshin' up, <br />
one of the loggers stuck his head in and tole me they was the best <br />
raisin muffins he'd ever had.  'Cept, I never put no raisins in 'em.  <br />
That was the rabbit's doin'.&quot;  Eleanor's  chuckle was two dry sticks <br />
rubbing together.  She took a hit off of her cigarette.<br />
     Bill smiled, wishing the old bitch would shut up and get their <br />
food.  He smelled the rich meat of the steaks frying on the greasy <br />
grill, and his mouth watered.  Lisa was still laughing, the silly <br />
little fool, with that raucous hyena's laugh of hers.  Miserable bitch <br />
looked like shit these days.  You had to turn the lights off just to <br />
get it up with the burnt-out skank hag anymore.<br />
     &quot;'Course, that ain't nearly as funny as the time my youngest had a <br />
bee fly up his pants leg...&quot;  Eleanor said.<br />
     Damn bitches fuckin' damn damn shit damn damn....<br />
<br />
<br />
     Pat and Kate reached the turnoff from the main highway just <br />
as the sun touched the peaks of the mountains across the canyon.  Pat <br />
drove down into the dim shadows at the end of a cloudy day.  Though the <br />
car was hot and stuffy, the twilight was cold.  Kate was asleep, her <br />
head nestled against Pat's shoulder.  She stirred in her sleep and said <br />
something incomprehensible.<br />
     As Pat drove deeper into the canyon, the light grew dimmer.  He <br />
switched on the headlights.  Snowflakes swirled before the headlights, <br />
not many but growing in number quickly until they became a gray curtain <br />
around the car.  Pat slowed down and looked for a place to park.  He <br />
came upon a roadside diner, and pulled into the tiny parking lot.  Kate <br />
woke up and yawned, asking sleepily &quot;Are we there yet?&quot;<br />
     The parking lot of the old diner was empty, apart from a pair of <br />
four-wheel-drive trucks.  An electric sign, missing a letter, flashed <br />
the message &quot;G od Eats.&quot;  An orange neon sign in the window advertised <br />
the fact that Budweiser was sold there.  A snowblower engine could be <br />
heard winding up around the back.<br />
     &quot;Not yet,&quot; he answered, &quot;We're stopping for a bite to eat.&quot;<br />
     &quot;Mm.  If God eats here, the food just has to be good.  Let's bring <br />
in my suitcase, I feel like I've been sleeping in these clothes.&quot;<br />
     &quot;I can't imagine why.  I'd better change too.  I have a wet spot <br />
on my shoulder where you were drooling.&quot;<br />
     &quot;Be happy women still drool over you.&quot;<br />
     &quot;Could you help an old man with the suitcases?&quot;<br />
     &quot;I suppose I should be rested up enough by now, considering I lost <br />
consciousness somewhere in Utah.&quot;<br />
     &quot;Well, don't expect me to drive back and help you look for it.&quot;<br />
     The snowblower shut down, and echoes rounded the valley.<br />
     When they opened the car doors the chill air swept through their <br />
clothing and through meat to strike bone.  They grabbed a couple of <br />
suitcases from the back seat and hustled into the diner.<br />
     Dingy yellow plastic made up most of the inside of the diner: <br />
seats patched with duct tape, formica tabletops, roses in empty beer <br />
bottles, and grayed linoleum.  Beer signs on the walls showed blue <br />
mountain streams, the &quot;water&quot; seeming to flow endlessly over electric <br />
waterfalls.  Along one wall, a row of trophies stared down with <br />
sightless eyes at the short bar and stained pool table.  A jukebox <br />
stood next to the bar, softly playing a country music song.  The dim <br />
lighting came from naked 60-watt bulbs in ceiling fixtures.<br />
     The wind blew against the door and windows behind them, but the <br />
diner was cozy and warm.  A smell of broiled beef and deep-fried <br />
potatoes filled the room, and the sound of Hank Williams singing &quot;Your <br />
Cheatin' Heart&quot; could be heard over the sounds of dishes being washed <br />
and cutlery clattering against plates.<br />
     A middle-aged couple sat in one of the booths, eating steak and <br />
french fries.  The man had thinning black hair and a thick neck covered <br />
with gun-metal stubble where no razor could ever get at it.  The woman <br />
had long blonde hair and a nervous expression.  They looked up as Pat <br />
and Kate came in, and the man raised his voice and called out:  <br />
&quot;Eleanor, you got a couple more customers here!&quot;<br />
     An elderly lady came out through the open kitchen door, wiping her <br />
hands on a dishtowel.<br />
     &quot;You folks just set yourselves down anywheres you like,&quot;  she said <br />
in a surprisingly deep baritone, grabbing a menu from the rack beside <br />
the cash register. &quot;I'll take your order right away.  I was just tryin' <br />
to clear a path to my trailer out back, and the dang 'blower ran outta <br />
gas!  What brings you folks out on an evenin' like this?&quot;<br />
     &quot;We were driving by when the snow started.  Lucky for us you're <br />
open.  Kate, you ready to order?&quot;<br />
     &quot;I'll have whatever these folks are having, it smells real good.  <br />
Excuse me just a minute.&quot;  Kate grabbed a suitcase and headed for the <br />
door marked &quot;Ladies.&quot;<br />
     &quot;Make that two of whatever these folks are having,&quot; Pat smiled at <br />
Eleanor, &quot;One medium and one medium rare.&quot;<br />
     &quot;You got it, that'll be about fifteen minutes.&quot;  Eleanor went to <br />
the kitchen and came back with place settings and poured two glasses of <br />
water.  As she went back into the kitchen, the man looked back at Pat <br />
and smiled with his mouth.<br />
     &quot;You live in Nueva City?  Nice town.  Nice and quiet.  Mostly <br />
loggers out this way.  What kinda work you do?&quot;<br />
     &quot;I write spy thrillers.  You know, the Cliff Benson series.&quot;<br />
     &quot;Never heard of it.&quot;<br />
     &quot;Yeah, well, it's pretty big back East.&quot;<br />
     &quot;A writer, eh?  Well, it takes all kinds.  By the way, my name is <br />
Bill, and this here is Lisa.&quot;<br />
     &quot;Pleased to meet you.  My name is Pat Kelly, and the woman in the <br />
bathroom is my wife, Kate.  She'd be pleased to meet you too, I'm <br />
sure.&quot;<br />
     &quot;I'd sure be pleased to meet her, that's for sure.&quot;  Bill made two <br />
quick turns of his wrist for emphasis.<br />
     &quot;Uh... Do you folks live up here, or are you visiting?&quot;  Pat asked <br />
quietly.<br />
     &quot;We come up every year for the fishing.  Lisa just loves to fish, <br />
don't you honey?&quot;<br />
     &quot;'Scuse me.&quot;  Lisa edged out of the booth and headed for the <br />
ladies room with a tight expression around her mouth.<br />
     &quot;Women.  Spend all the damn time in the bathroom.&quot;  Bill observed.  <br />
Pat acknowledged with the slightest of nods.<br />
     Bill looked Pat over.  Not quite as young as he looks, he thought.  <br />
Closer to my age.  Kind of homely-looking with all those freckles, <br />
probably looks like Howdy Doody without that eyepatch.  Wonder how he <br />
lost the arm...<br />
     &quot;Pat.  You mind if I ask you a question?&quot;    <br />
     &quot;Ask away.&quot;<br />
     &quot;How'd you lose your arm and eye?&quot;<br />
     &quot;It's pretty simple,&quot; he replied, &quot;I lost them in Vietnam.&quot;<br />
     &quot;Yeah?  I was in 'Nam too.  Hey!  Want to see the fish I caught?  <br />
They're in my truck.&quot;<br />
     &quot;Sure.  Let me get my coat on.&quot;<br />
     The two men put on their coats and went out to the parking lot.  <br />
The snow was still falling.<br />
<br />
<br />
     Kate was brushing her hair in the bathroom when a knock came from <br />
the door.<br />
     &quot;Come in.&quot;  She turned, and the young woman with long blonde hair <br />
came in and shut the door.  She looked like she was ready to cry, and <br />
Kate asked &quot;Are you okay, honey?&quot;<br />
     The tears started to come then, against the woman's will, <br />
squeezing past her self-control as little hot bullets of despair.<br />
     &quot;I've tried so hard to get that man to love me, and all I've <br />
accomplished is that I'm beginning to hate him.&quot;<br />
     Kate resigned herself to the dreary role of Bathroom Counselor, <br />
and put her arm around the woman's shoulders.<br />
     &quot;Now, it can't be as bad as all that...&quot;<br />
<br />
<br />
          Bill pulled back the tarp on the nearest of the two pickups, <br />
and motioned Pat to come and look.  In the bed of the pickup was a <br />
basket full of dry ice and dead fish.<br />
     Bill opened the unlocked door of the truck, and pulled a hunting <br />
rifle from the rack.<br />
     &quot;Thirty-ought-six,&quot; he said proudly. &quot;Blow a hole through an <br />
elephant the size of my fist.&quot;<br />
     Pat said, through teeth clenched with cold, &quot;I think I heard <br />
something in that ditch across the road.  Sounds like a kid crying.&quot;<br />
     &quot;I'll take a look.&quot;  Bill walked across the road, still carrying <br />
the rifle, and peered into the ditch.       &quot;Nope, nothing in here but <br />
snow.&quot;<br />
     At that moment a deer came running down the road, a three-point <br />
buck galloping stiff-legged on tiptoes.  Bill raised the rifle to his <br />
shoulder, sighted, fired, missed.  The buck scrambled down the slopes <br />
into the dark before the echoes had died.<br />
<br />
<br />
     Eleanor finished filling the tank of the snowblower, then put the <br />
cap back loosely on the gas can.  She dragged the heavy snowblower out <br />
the back door, knocking over the gas can in the process.  The clear, <br />
slightly pink fluid gushed over the kitchen floor.  As she came back in <br />
from the cold, Eleanor slipped on the wet floor, dropping her <br />
cigarette.<br />
<br />
<br />
     &quot;He's just gotten worse every year since he got home from <br />
Vietnam,&quot;  said Lisa.  &quot;He doesn't have any friends except his army <br />
buddies, and he's gotten so rude and mean that nobody wants anything to <br />
do with us.  Was your husband in the war?  If he was, I bet that's what <br />
they're talking about right now.&quot;<br />
     &quot;No, Pat wasn't in the war.  He wasn't eligible for the service <br />
because he lost an arm and an eye in a traffic accident when he was <br />
nine.  He wanted to go real bad, too, to be with his brother in the <br />
Marines.  His brother never came back, though.  Hey, do you smell <br />
something?&quot;<br />
<br />
<br />
     &quot;Missed the sonofabitch!&quot; howled Bill.<br />
     &quot;Do you leave your gun loaded in an unlocked truck all the time?&quot; <br />
asked Pat.<br />
     &quot;My weapon is always loaded.  Say, what branch of the service were <br />
you in?&quot;<br />
     &quot;Uh, the Marines.&quot;<br />
     &quot;What outfit?&quot;<br />
     &quot;I don't like to talk about the war.&quot;<br />
     &quot;Okay.  Lisa don't like it much when I talk about the war either, <br />
or when I get my army buddies to come over for poker.  I'd trade her in <br />
for a newer model, but we been married twenty-two years last July, and <br />
you know what they mean when they say Semper Fidelis.&quot;<br />
     &quot;No, what?&quot;<br />
     &quot;I knew it!  You weren't in no Marines at all!  No marine would <br />
call a rifle a gun, and Semper Fidelis is the Corps' motto.  You lyin' <br />
sack of shit!&quot;<br />
     &quot;Where do you think I lost my arm?  You think I lost my eye <br />
because I left the spoon in my coffee?&quot;<br />
     Pat turned towards the diner, away from Bill.  Then the diner <br />
exploded.  The explosion knocked both Pat and Bill down, but both of <br />
them got up again immediately.<br />
     &quot;Lisa!  Oh my god, Lisa!&quot;  Bill yelled, looking wildly around him <br />
as if help could come out of the shadows.  <br />
     Pat ran past Bill, into the burning diner, but the door to the <br />
ladies room was barred by a collapsed beam, and screams came from <br />
within.  He looked around, and saw a fire extinguisher, an axe, and an <br />
alarm switch behind a sheet of glass.  He smashed the glass, pulled the <br />
switch, and grabbed the axe with his hand.  He swung at the beam until <br />
it broke in two, and he dug the axe into the severed beam and dragged <br />
it away from the door.  The door opened, and Kate and Lisa came out.  <br />
They ran to the front door and were out, while Pat searched for <br />
Eleanor.  The heat from the fire, mostly in the back of the diner, <br />
increased, so Pat ran out the front door just as the roof fell in.<br />
<br />
<br />
     Bill stood in the snow and watched the diner burn.  He thought of <br />
Vietnam, again, remembering his first week there, the week of his <br />
eighteenth birthday.  After the drop, his first, they had pulled back <br />
some.  Bill hadn't fired the machine gun even once.  He looked back <br />
over his shoulder to make some wisecrack about milk runs, when the <br />
rocket hit.<br />
     The chopper spun in, while Bill hung on and screamed at the top of <br />
his lungs.  He didn't remember the crash itself;  he remembered waking <br />
up afterwards, a bag full of sharp broken sticks and unbearable agony.  <br />
The goddamn chopper was on fire!  He crawled out through a crack in the <br />
fuselage, and was trying to get as much distance as possible between <br />
him and the chopper when the pilot woke up.  He could hear the screams, <br />
so much like a baby in pain.<br />
     Twenty hours later, he was found and rescued.  Eight weeks <br />
afterwards he was on the Cambodian border, fighting a dirty war against <br />
a bunch of skinny kids.<br />
     &quot;Bill...&quot;  He turned and Lisa was standing there, shivering.  <br />
&quot;What's the matter?&quot;<br />
     &quot;Nothing matters any more except us.&quot;  He wrapped his arms around <br />
her and held her against the cold.  Snow fell across their embrace and <br />
melted away.  They were still holding each other when the fire trucks <br />
came up the road.<br />
<br />
<br />
     In the fire station, Pat and Kate sat close and shared warmth, <br />
waiting for their statements to be typed, so they could sign them and <br />
be on their way.  Bill and Lisa had escaped this chore by slipping into <br />
their truck and driving away while the firemen were busy hosing down <br />
the embers.  The fire department suspected that Eleanor had left a can <br />
of gasoline near the water heater.  All that was left of Eleanor and <br />
the Good Eats Diner was a blackened mess by the side of the road and <br />
some paperwork downtown.  No more stories and hot black coffee.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
